results.notes:
In the spruce stands both L. lignyotus and L gerardii are common. When lignyotus has matured, the gill separation approaches distant and the cap color fades. The two types can be tricky to differentiate. In the case of the mushroom seen here, the gills are more pigmented than what is expected with gerardii (photo shows them paler than true color). But the really telling difference seems to be the unusually long spines on the spores of lignyotus.

Spores 8-10 × 7.5-9.

results.notes:
Growing gregariously – singly and in clusters – in the vicinity of a large pin oak and several white pines after the big rains. This species has been observed growing regularly at this site (at least one fruiting per year) over the last several years, e.g., obs 207987, obs 210360, and obs 243519. This time I was able to catch them in a very fresh state (they degrade quickly in situ and squirrels love them, too!), but alas the flesh in the bottom of stipe had already suffered water and insect damage. The cap color though is gorgeous.
Typically, the fruiting bodies are small, with caps usually not exceeding 2", but the cap of 210360 (which I called B. subraternus) was 3.7" across. Cap surface cracking is minimal. Based on this trait, as well as the fact that the flesh in the lower half of stipe is reddish-orange, H. campestris can be eliminated (BENA). The angular pores and tubes are concolorous, yellow to greenish-yellow, readily bruising greenish-blue to blue; pores getting larger toward the stipe, pore surface irregular. The stipe is yellow at the apex and reddish-orange below, either smooth entirely or noticeably ridged in the apex, some dots and punctae visible in the upper stipe; basal mycelium whitish to pale yellow, creeping as a dusting along the stipe. The exposed flesh in the cap and upper stipe is light to medium yellow, sometimes bright yellow, bluing slowly just above the tubes and at the cap-stipe juncture.

results.notes:
This came from near the fire tower parking lot at Cook’s forest, growing in moss under red oak. If I had to place a bet I would say this is the “true” Baorangia while the ones I find closer to home, with stouter and more mixed-yellow stipes, are in some other genus or three. But who knows? DNA will out. There is no doubt that people in this part of the country call this “bicolor”. It was viewed on site by both JP3 and Walt Sturgeon, who agreed with that (but without taking a stand on what DNA might say when all is said and done).

The stipe was almost entirely red on all specimens with bare hints of yellow. No reticulation or other markings and it did not change color when bruised. White mycelium.

Caps were red, getting more cracked and paler with age. Chemical tests were identical on the redder and the paler parts of the cap and stipe skin.

Cap flesh was very pale yellow while the stipe flesh was a darker yellow. Chemical test reactions were notably faster and stronger on the yellower flesh, which suggests that the reactions might be related to the amount of natural pigment.

Tubes and pores were yellow, darkening with age. Pores bruised dark blue readily and eventually resolved to dark brown. Old, naturally damaged pores often displayed a red staining instead.

The largest, uncollectably old specimen I found this time had a cap that was around 10 cm (approximately 4") across.

These are a typical bolete when it comes to texture, odor, taste, and heft. They get quite marshmallowy in old age but otherwise have average firmness.

No particular odor or taste was noted.

NOTE ON PHOTOS: All chemical tests go in the order ammonia, then KOH, then FeSO4 moving from left to right

Ammonia on Red Cap Skin: No strong reaction.
Ammonia on Tan Cap Skin: No strong reaction.

KOH on Young Pores: Turned orange faster than the paler cap flesh.

FeSO4 on Red Cap Skin: Slow olive.
FeSO4 on Tan Cap Skin: Slow olive.
FeSO4 on Stipe Skin: Slow olive.
FeSO4 on Cap Context: Turned olive.

COMMON NAME = Purple-spored Puffball

NEARBY FLORA: Heather, mixed perennials.
SUBSTRATE: Grass lawn, flower bed with humus soil.
HABIT: Single to Few….generally 3 specimens aggregated to form a peanut or grape-cluster shape that varies in size from ~ 1 ” x ~ ½” to ~ 3 “ x ~ 1 ” . Two more older specimens, growing separately, but close. All specimens were owing in mostly bare soil areas, and exist in shaded, partially sunny, and full-sun areas.
ODOR: Non-descript.
TASTE: According to sources it is considered poisonous.

DETAILED PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION:

CAP: 10 specimens found over a 2-day period.

Younger specimens (6) are Individual specimens are generally “call-out” shaped, ranging in width from ~ ⅛”, ~ ¼”, and ~ ½”, ~ 1”, and ~ 1.5”, and ranging in height from ~ ¼ “, ~ ½ “, ~1”, and ~ 1.5”. Surface is a light tan on 7 larger specimens, approximately 1mm thick, with what is best described as irregularly shaped darker-brown dots (a.k.a., cracking) over the entire surface…dot sizes are irregular as well (from ~ 1 – 3mm in size). This cracking is barely felt when moving a finger over the surface. The white case turns a light pink when cut,

On the older specimens the top is plate-like, with the underside being smooth and slowly tapering to the base. Size is ~ 1 ¼” across and ~ ½” deep . The top has the same cracking as the smaller samples and has medium tan to brown coloring, with the dots continuing slightly over past the edges into the underside area. Underside color is yellow-ochre to medium tan, and most of the surface has none of the cracking of the younger samples.

BASE: Smaller, aggregate sample: White with splotches of very-light brown, tapered, with an inverted equilateral-triangle-shape appearance with an approximate size of ¼” per side. It appears the fruit grows irregularly from the triangular base. The surface appears rough/warty.

Larger, separate, aggregate samples, and older samples: Light-brown to egg-shell color, with the structure looking like a tree root, with many larger-to-smaller branches, almost a nerve-cell, capillary-like appearance. Length is ~ ¾ ” and top width is ~ ½”. These bruise a light-pink when cut.

SPORE MASS:
None of the specimens have a white center, including the younger, firmer ones. Inside these specimens, the mass is a dark purple when first cut open, becoming lighter within 24 hours and having a slight greyish-brown hue visible, and darker with age.

MYCELIA: White, very dense, running out from the base in several directions.

COMMON NAME: Almond-scented Russula

NEARBY TREES: Conifer, Douglas, Hemlock, Silver, and a few Vine Maples
SUBSTRATE: Leaf Litter, Dense Humus Soil, Needle Duff, and Moss. Soil was slightly damp.
HABIT: Few (2 within 6-inch area). Found near the edge of what is normally a wetland area….lots of damp mud, but no standing water. A great deal of Vanilla Leaf plants (Achlys triphylla) exist throughout the area.
ODOR: Indistinct, ostensibly Almond.
TASTE: Acrid, Peppery

DETAILED PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION:

CAP: Largest specimen is ~1.5” wide, with the smaller at ~.75” wide. Hemispheric, smooth…but with very-fine bumps over the entire cuticle; Color is predominantly tan…darker at the center & lighter towards the margin…there are numerous, irregularly placed darker tan splotches, and the cuticle cracks w/age. Flesh is white, thick, very firm, and turning very-light tan where cut or bruised. Somewhat viscid/tacky when wet. Margin is in-rolled, very finely scalloped, and irregularly crenulated, with distinct sharp edges. The Margin of the smaller specimen is very-much in-rolled, to the point that it is folded up into the gill area.

GILLS: Bone-white, notched, close-to-crowded, but fairly equally spaced. Pale tan where cut or bruised.

STIPE: Bone-white in the upper-third, with vertically striated or banded areas of light-to-medium tan feathering of the remainder of the surface area. It is clavate, with central attachment, slowly tapering to bottom. The surface is smooth, but has irregularly shaped undulations…mixed vertically and horizontally across the stipe. There are also numerous, irregularly shaped, shallow pits on the stipe surface. The flesh is bone-white and very-firm, with no visible color-change where cut or bruised.

NOTE: The Stipe of both specimens, including the smaller one, has been invaded by some type of insect. The larger specimen has a bore-hole near the stipe bottom and about two-thirds of the interior has been eaten away, leaving “shelves” of uneaten flesh where it appears the insect used these shelves as a platform to eat from. A quarter-inch long thrip-like insect was observed exiting one of the halves of the larger specimen.

SPORES: unknown at this time.

MYCELIA: White, very dense, directly below the forest duff. Appears to run shallow in the packed substrate, ~ 1/16”.

MO#: 334006 iNat #: 16733185

COMMON NAME: Barrow’s Bolete

NOTE: This Bolete is usually found in Idaho, southern Callifornia, and New Mexico. It has also been found in Seattle, WA under hardwoods. The specimens found were growing under an imported Birch tree from the eastern US.

NEARBY FLORA: Beech Tree….identification confirmed with WA State biologist.
SUBSTRATE: Grass interspersed w/Moss on top of soil.
HABIT: 20+ in a 10’ x 20’ area, Northwest of the Main Admin Center bldg.
LIGHT EXPOSURE: Shade to Partial Shade
ODOR: Pleasant Mushroom.
TASTE: Nutty

DETAILED PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION:

CAP: 1” – 12” across, depending on age. Convex, becoming almost flat or even wavy in older specimens that are close together; buff colored at first, becoming a light brown on older specimens; dry, bald, featuring irregularly shaped, shallow cracks with age.

PORES: Free from Stipe. When viewed from the bottom on older specimens, the pores are free from Stipe with an obvious sloped channel (about ¼” deep) between stipe and pore surface. Younger specimens do not have this channel and the pore area appears to “stuff” the entire cap underside. Pore surface is white at first, becoming a pale yellow, and finally having an olive yellow coloration. No bruising when cut. 1-2 pores/mm and up to 1.5” deep at maturity. When removed from large specimens the cap underside has yellow staining against a predominantly white area.

STIPE: Shape varies from Clavate to Tapered. The Tapered variation, when viewed from the bottom, has a somewhat elliptical appearance. Length varies from1” – 6” tall, with a thickness of 1” to 2”. The stipe is very solid, having a buff coloring that has light-brown fine reticulation over most of the surface area. Flesh is white, firm, with some minor staining in the area just above where the stipe makes contact with the substrate surface. This stain is a light brown.

SPORES: Olive Brown

MYCELIA: White, very dense, running shallow in the packed substrate, ~ ½”
